WEBVTT

00:01.887 --> 00:02.888
José María Garza. Yes. And where was he born? He 
didn't return to Vieja García. In what year? 1906.

00:10.697 --> 00:13.800
And when did he live in Ateas? In 1914. And for what 
reason? For the revolution. Ah, yes. And tell me

00:19.327 --> 00:22.610
more about the revolution in these days, please. 
Well, before that date when we came here, when we

00:24.633 --> 00:31.320
lived in Vieja García, My father was in charge 
there. And when the revolutionaries came in, they

00:35.324 --> 00:39.089
came with the... He was in charge there. And to give 
them reason where there was corn, food, whatever.

00:48.101 --> 00:52.807
And they went and looted

00:48.101 --> 00:52.807
everything. And at that time, at about two or three 
o'clock, those revolutionaries came out and the

00:52.827 --> 00:57.373
federals came in. They were from the government. 
After a while, they were thrown out of the

01:00.983 --> 01:07.991
billiards and the billiardsmen came in. After a 
while, a bandit from Tolentino came in with

01:08.011 --> 01:12.656
people. And that's when the federalists came in 
again, the trebadores from La Huerta. There was a

01:17.262 --> 01:20.686
day when the money changed every two hours. It was 
so cheap, it was worth a kind of money. It was in

01:23.869 --> 01:27.614
paper, billiards that they named it. Some bills in 
pesos, in cincos. In half an hour it was worth a

01:30.683 --> 01:36.390
coin, in half an hour another, and it was like that. 
And there were dead people hanging there. They

01:38.472 --> 01:42.037
were carried in carts. They were dodged like 
dodging firewood. And there, on the riverbank,

01:45.801 --> 01:50.747
they made a well for them, they called it the 
caracol. There they just lit the yunta and emptied

01:50.767 --> 01:53.951
them to the dead. There they were carried.

01:58.937 --> 02:00.319
And that's when he took... Francisco could not get 
out via Nicamole and Nacataz. There is a stream of

02:07.934 --> 02:23.833
the Cerro del Fraile that goes all the way here, all 
the way to Mediación, via Gacía, via Gacía's

02:07.934 --> 02:23.833
plains. And they used it as a fence, the billets. 
And from there, from Sierra Madre, another came.

02:29.425 --> 02:35.615
It was just a river, a stream, and they couldn't get 
out of sight. General Alfonso Vázquez came and

02:35.636 --> 02:42.768
started to bring people in. As he was in charge, 
they were gathering. They were from the

02:45.673 --> 02:50.100
government who were coming that day. They were 
there for three days, and when they had parking

02:50.587 --> 03:00.279
spaces in black boxes, that was the park, they 
would come in and accommodate him there. At three

03:00.339 --> 03:07.589
in the morning, they gave orders to throw 
Francisco Villa there. If he turned back, they

03:07.669 --> 03:09.051
would thrash him. It was a push for a decision. And 
they came in at about eight in the morning, and

03:14.217 --> 03:19.063
people started to come out. By ten, they started to 
get injured. They brought them home and brought

03:21.181 --> 03:24.165
them to Monterrey. At two in the afternoon, 
General Alfonso Vázquez was killed. He was shot

03:29.834 --> 03:30.535
three times. He didn't want to be brought back from 
combat. He wanted three captains. When he arrived

03:37.785 --> 03:39.668
in Monterrey, he died. But the people of General 
Alfonso Vázquez never came back until Francisco

03:40.489 --> 03:47.219
Villa was thrown out. In the port of... Why did you 
explain?

04:20.868 --> 04:45.070
He clarified, part of

04:20.868 --> 04:45.070
your question was, he clarified

04:20.868 --> 04:45.070
that there were

04:20.868 --> 04:45.070
different groups. My father had a lot of corn and 
everything. There was whatever they wanted. If

04:52.790 --> 04:59.362
you turned to the other side, they would kill you. 
You had to be with them if they wanted to be with us.

05:05.533 --> 05:08.158
Don't go against them. Don't oppose them. Because 
there were too many groups. Who were they going to

05:13.518 --> 05:16.402
favor? And so they really were neutral. Right. But 
they were the ones that were getting screwed, you

05:20.186 --> 05:23.270
know? Right, right. The machine guns. What kind of 
work did your father have before the revolution?

05:30.458 --> 05:33.041
He was a carpenter. He made bagpipes. Morales. 
Riatas del azar. carpets, and a lot of other things

05:39.421 --> 05:48.692
that are from Istria. What did you do with them? 
From Istria. What was that? Mamey. From Lechuvía.

05:55.079 --> 05:55.900
From Lechuvía. And he was the owner there? He was 
the owner. And what did those lands do? They left

06:00.746 --> 06:01.747
them there. They left them there. We also have 
lands there. If we don't pay taxes, we have

06:04.430 --> 06:07.073
nothing. And they came to Laredo, Texas. to work in 
the bakery. Our older brothers were bakers. Your

06:20.345 --> 06:21.766
older brothers? How did they learn that trade in 
Spanish? The trade. The trade. In the bakeries,

06:28.154 --> 06:33.340
dad would put them to work, to teach them. Aunque 
les pagaran poquito, pero que aprendieran. He's a

06:38.163 --> 06:39.786
baker by trade also. He's a jack of all trades. Ah, y 
así aprendió usted de panadero también. Y

06:47.117 --> 06:53.887
trabajamos en... Ahí en Laredo trabajaron de 
panaderos. En 1915. In 1915 we started working in

06:56.118 --> 07:02.344
the panadería El Gallo, in Larero. In Larero. In 
Larero. There we worked. His name was Raúl

07:04.846 --> 07:09.130
Ornelas, the owner of the bakery. And one of his 
sons was Luque Ornelas. We worked there. And at 17

07:15.496 --> 07:18.019
we came here to Camargo. And from Camargo we moved 
here to Rio Grande. To work in the bakery. And my

07:22.423 --> 07:24.505
brothers were teachers. He's got a brother that

07:25.210 --> 07:49.497
lives

07:25.210 --> 07:49.497
in Monterrey,

07:25.210 --> 07:49.497
Mexico. And you came here to the United States, 
from Camargo. Yes, from Camargo. They brought us

07:54.546 --> 07:55.348
here. After the Revolution. After the 
Revolution. Why did you come to Texas? Because

07:59.254 --> 08:03.200
from here we went to look for Leopoldo Reynaga, who 
was a baker. But you had a lot of knowledge here in

08:03.340 --> 08:06.666
Rio Grande, right? Yes, because of the question of 
being bakers. And they brought us here so that we

08:09.831 --> 08:14.218
could work there. And why did you stay here in 
Texas? Why did your brother Felipe return to

08:16.301 --> 08:18.184
Mexico? But he never lived in Texas. I was working 
here in Texas, but because he was a mechanic, any

08:21.108 --> 08:39.898
motor that he heard working, he worked in Peñoles, 
in a factory where he was in charge of just

08:21.108 --> 08:39.898
following the engine that was failing, he would 
tell them to drive it. But he came back, he

08:39.918 --> 08:43.804
preferred to go to Mexico to stay here. Yes, he did. 
Y nosotros, pues, aquí estábamos sacando bien la

08:46.666 --> 08:51.631
vida hasta la fecha. Ya no nos movimos. Trabajé el 
25. En 1924, trabajamos

08:56.075 --> 09:04.342
en San Antonio, en la panadería de Jacobo Estrada. 
Era una de las mejores panaderías que había. Y ahí

09:08.466 --> 09:10.568
trabajé en Houston. Bueno, usted nació en Villa 
García, ¿no? En Villa García.

09:18.458 --> 09:25.329
When was it that the U.S. took, they made the Rio 
Grande border, you know, the American border? Oh,

09:25.349 --> 09:25.709
1845. That was in 1845. That was way after the 
revolution. So that means that these people, when

09:29.435 --> 09:34.923
they crossed that border, they were actually 
crossing into a foreign country. They were

09:34.943 --> 09:36.546
crossing into a foreign country. So, ¿cómo se 
quedaban aquí legalmente? Why would the U.S.

09:38.609 --> 09:40.372
government let them do that? I don't know. How did 
they cross the border without the American

09:43.248 --> 09:48.295
government telling them? We crossed in Laredo and 
they just pointed us out. That's the date. They

09:53.902 --> 09:55.224
were just right on us. They were just right on us. 
That's the date. And then when we came here, we came

09:57.327 --> 10:01.152
here, they charged us with passports. And when 
they arrived, they charged us with passports. We

10:04.276 --> 10:05.978
went through the bridge with permission. They 
took our passports. And then when the $8 passports

10:07.300 --> 10:11.145
arrived, we took them out. Everyone took out their 
passports. The first time they crossed? You, when

10:16.207 --> 10:16.808
you crossed? There wasn't. There wasn't? There 
wasn't a passport. You crossed in 1903? Yes. And

10:22.276 --> 10:23.418
there wasn't a passport? There wasn't 
immigration? Yes, the reason why we were

10:25.741 --> 10:28.706
registered. Ah, they would just record. Ah, they 
just wrote the names of the people. They didn't

10:33.172 --> 10:34.695
write anything. And they were registered there. 
Did it stay there? There was no limit to how long

10:40.086 --> 10:42.950
they could stay here. There was no limit. The years 
went by. When did the American government require

10:47.735 --> 10:56.786
the registration? Around 1918. So what did they 
do? When the American government demanded

11:03.542 --> 11:07.867
that... The passports were $10. They

11:09.909 --> 11:22.803
could have stayed here in the United States for as 
long as they wanted.

11:25.425 --> 11:29.850
Right, that's what... In fact, there weren't even 
closed checks a lot of places. A lot of places you

11:33.774 --> 11:37.480
just walked across and nobody even asked you to 
sign your name. Like I say, the people that lived

11:37.500 --> 11:41.406
here, the people that lived there were the same 
people. Right, right. And the border was

11:42.929 --> 11:44.952
absolutely big. In fact, it was up in the 20s that 
the first real... close checks began to be made,

11:51.008 --> 12:02.961
and it wasn't until about 1930 or in the early 30s 
that there was any officially enforced

11:51.008 --> 12:02.961
close-ups. That's when she found out that she was 
an American citizen, when they started enforcing

12:03.761 --> 12:08.867
it. In the 1930s. Right. She was going to go get her 
official citizenship, and she said, you're

12:10.569 --> 12:19.598
already a citizen. What year were you married? The 
first time. In 1924. A woman from here or from

12:27.039 --> 12:31.745
Mexico? From here. From the United States? From 
the United States. What was her name? Maria

12:42.939 --> 12:43.680
Aguirre. And she was from Texas? She was from 
Texas. She was from Texas? Yes. And here in Rio

12:53.479 --> 12:54.881
Grande. How did her family come here to Rio Grande? 
We lived here. We lived here. I don't know. They

12:59.988 --> 13:03.893
probably emigrated in the same conditions. My 
husband lived over there

13:03.913 --> 13:10.301
in Rivera. He lived over there in Rivera. It was 
Rivera. Well, sir, tell

13:15.046 --> 13:34.076
me a little more about life here in the United 
States. Could it be that you were kidnapped again?

13:40.987 --> 13:41.087
What? Well, tell me a little more about your life 
here in the United States. Well, here in the United

13:45.329 --> 13:51.418
States I've had a good time. I've always worked. 
Yes. And we, as we had a bakery office, they came to

13:53.361 --> 13:58.468
take us from various places. Once, they took me to 
El Cauce, to San Juan, to Quinisville, to... San

14:09.417 --> 14:16.344
Antonio also took me to Dílete, or Mílete, how is 
San Antonio? Dílete, yes, or Mílete, it's over

14:16.364 --> 14:18.607
there. Two little places, there's Cotula too. 
There have always been better jobs than on the

14:24.473 --> 14:29.278
other side. We knew how to work in the bakery, and we 
still had the fame of bakers, because we were

14:29.598 --> 14:38.968
bakers, and we still are.

